Marathon ministry…sharing my priestly heart,
Encouraging souls at the finish and the start.
Working through injuries, pain and falling apart,
Runners are resilient...I’m grateful to take part!

Bio
Matt Maher has become one of the most popular and critically acclaimed Catholic artists in the country. Originally from Newfoundland, Canada, he got his start in church music at St. Timothy Catholic Church in Mesa, Arizona, while studying jazz at Arizona State University in Tempe.

Matt has consistently provided the Church with songs expressing God's greatness and our need for his grace. Since the 2002 release of his first CD, The End and the Beginning, the rise of Matt and his music has been remarkable. His songs have been recorded by Kathy Troccoli and Chris Tomlin (“Your Grace Is Enough”) and have received multiple Grammy nominations. He sang “I Need You, Lord” before Pope Francis and a crowd of four million people at World Youth Day 2013 in Brazil. His latest realease, Echoes, features songs of God's love in the wake of personal tragedy.

Matt and his band travel worldwide throughout the year to bring their signature brand of praise and worship to young audiences through a variety of concert events.

He currently lives in Nashville with his wife and children.

Eight years ago at the age of 49, I made a decision to hang up my hockey skates, basketball shoes, and tennis racket, and begin to focus on running marathons.  Grateful to God for giving me the health and fortitude to have finished my 8th marathon two weeks ago at 57 years old, with a pr of 3:32 and my 2nd Boston qualifying time.  My goal has always been to improve in everything, with the hope of being a better instrument as a Catholic priest in God's hands.  Next stop: DC Rock and Roll Half Marathon on March 18th...striving for another pr, offering it all up for vocations!  Have a blessed week-end and final stretch to Christmas! #marathon #marathontraining #marathoner #marathoners #marathonrunner #themarathoncontinues

Grateful to God for the gift of life, the gift of my priesthood and the gift of healthy running legs at 57...but I know that to achieve pr's and bq's, the hard work needs to put in on the trail...all for vocations and God's glory! 
“Running is just you, the work you put in, and the clock. You can’t cheat yourself. If you don’t put in the miles, you can’t go to the starting line thinking you’re going to pull a miracle out of nowhere. You get out exactly what you put in.” -Des Linden, 2018 Boston Marathon women’s winner

Since his major-label debut in 2008, Matt Maher has become a staple in the artistic and songwriting community. A nine-time-GRAMMY® nominee and three-time-GMA Dove Award® winner, he has garnered multiple radio successes, writing and recording songs such as his Top 5 CCLI song “Lord, I Need You” and the chart-topping radio singles “Because He Lives (Amen)” and “Alive & Breathing.” Along with other hits such as “Hold Us Together,” “Christ Is Risen,” “All The People Said Amen,” and “Your Grace Is Enough,” Maher has written or co-written six No. 1 radio singles.

God bless,

 As we approach the month of May, I am reminded of a Marian Miracle that happened in the backyard of a New Jersey family.  During my Lumen chaplain days in NJ, I would try to get around to visit the various families for dinner and offer a house blessing.  Ray and Angela Burns lived a little further away than the others, so after driving over an hour for dinner, they asked when I would be back for a visit.  I told them them that I would come back in a few months if they put a Marian grotto in their back yard.  A few weeks later, Ray informed me that they had put a Marian statue under their cherry blossom tree and she was waiting for a priestly blessing.  This tree had never blossomed in their many years in this house, but since Mary arrived the tree has blossomed brilliantly every Spring.  Ray sent me this recent photo a few weeks ago….God is always working!

 October, 1979.  Freshman year cross country at Brother Rice High School, in Bloomfield Hills, Michigan…my best time for a 5k race was 19:36 (6:19 per mile). I shifted to play Varsity soccer, and then dedicated the next 35 years to focus on soccer, basketball and hockey, playing on different men’s and Parish teams as a means to evangelize that world as a Catholic priest. 
  October, 2015.  Thanks to Tony MacDonnell (pictured below), a Regnum Christi consecrated man, I ran my first marathon in Hartford, Connecticut.  8 marathons (including Boston last year), and 8 half marathons later, I did a full circle this morning and ran my first 5k race in 44 years (21:10- 6:46 pace per mile). 
  I am very grateful to Tony and to all those who have encouraged me along this path (Fr. Daniel Pajerski, LC, Miguel Valero, Joe Hart, Jeff Moore, Beth Grimes, Mary Bloom, Joe Findaro, Erica, Brendan and Ben)…and I am really looking forward to the Boston and Chicago Marathons in 2024! I am very grateful to God as well for giving me the gift of  good health and for being injury free!  I offer up all of these hard training runs and races for more priestly vocations, and I hope to inspire older runners to stick with it…you can get faster!!

God bless you,
FrMichael Sliney, LC #marathon #marathontraining #5k #5krun #5km #running #run #priestrunner #catholic

Just before beginning my run on this soupy DC day, I received a text message from a young couple that I attend in spiritual direction.  The wife was about to undergo an emergency c section for twin boys (their first children) and they were asking for prayers...so, I said a few prayers immediately, and then I offered up my speed work on the canal for this intention.  I was so happy to receive this text message when I returned to my car:
"Baby Michael was born at 5.4 pounds and baby Matthew at 5 pounds - both babies have a little NICU time to get stronger but are perfectly healthy. Mom is doing wonderful and I’m in recovery now!"

Marathon ministry!  As a Catholic priest, I am always on the look-out for souls who may need a kind word or a boost along the running trails. 

Mile 3: I passed a middle aged gentleman going at a solid 8 min. per mile clip and then within a minute, he pulled up and began to pass me...so we began to talk. He is a marathoner from California who unfortunately is in the process of getting divorced...I think he was surprised and happy to hear I was a Catholic priest. 

Mile 10: I came up to a younger runner on the uphill climb of the Capital Crescent trail...he had a big smile when I started talking with him.  He is training for the Berlin marathon.  We went deep pretty quickly.  He asked me if I spoke with Jesus during my runs and I shared with him that I do enjoy running in silence at times to have these prolonged chats with Jesus (as well as listening to Christian music). We also agreed that the key to life is trying to conform our will to God's will, to become less self absorbed and try our best to truly care about others. 

*This is what makes my 12 mile runs special...when I can have a few of these "God moments" on the trail, and it made today's hot and humid run a bit more pleasant!  Have a blessed week-end!

Marathon ministry:  Most runners are surprised to hear that they are suddenly running with a Catholic priest, and the Boston running shirt always sparks an interesting conversation!
Mile 3- I caught up to an active duty Marine who is training for the Marine Corps marathon in October. Providentially, his wife is from my home town of Bloomfield Hills, Michigan and we discussed the importance of forming his 3 teenage kids in the Faith.  We also agreed how good it was for "forming the will" by training in soupy DC weather.
Mile 5- I saw two older Korean runners cruising along up towards me from the opposite direction...I recognized them from the Asian running club, and one of them called out "Father Michael" and we gave each other a big "high five" with a smile.
Mile 6- I noticed a blind walker gradually coming towards me, with his stick sweeping the path, so I shouted out, "Have a blessed day!"...he was caught off guard, but responded happily "Oh...God bless you too!"
Mile 8- a yellow vested runner was keeping a solid pace up the long hill on the Crescent trail...as I caught up to him, he told me that he has run all the major marathons and he is 68 years old...and he is hoping to qualify for Boston when he turns 70.  He mentioned the importance of clean living, and said, "Father, I suppose you have that one figured out!"
Mile 10- A much older runner was shuffling along up the trail and I noticed he had triathlon shirt on...he is 78 years old and is still doing triathlons!  I told him that I hope to still be on the trail in 20 years like him, he said, "Keep running and you will be on the trail for the next 40 years!"
It's always interesting to interact with strangers...it's like reading a new book; you just don't know what you will get. Have a blessed day, everyone!

Marathon ministry!
Mile 5: It took me awhile to catch up to these two running buddies...they are in their 40's and ran track together in High School.  One of the gentleman has two young kids and he agreed that he and his wife need to start going to Church every Sunday for the good of the kids and their marriage. 
Mile 6: I asked a 75 year old biker if he could take this picture at my turn around near the Key Bridge.  He told me that he was from New York and attended Catholic schools through High School but he has not been practicing since that time.  He said "I did enough Novenas as a kid to gain an insurance policy for heaven." I told him there is no disadvantage in trying to reconnect with God...he agreed but when I offered him my priestly blessing at the end, he said, "No Thank you...but thanks for all the good that you are doing out there."
Mile 8: I recognized a 68 year old runner who beat me out at my last park run, even though I had a "pr" of a 6:46 pace...he runs this 5k every Saturday and he had a big smile on his face as I said "God bless you" as we ran by each other. 
Mile 9: I caught up to a DC running group of over 70 runners...one of the leaders tried to encourage me to join this group, but I told him that I am a Catholic priest and it would be hard for me to commit to a regular running schedule...he and his friends were a bit surprised to hear that I was a priest!
Mile 11: Two ladies running in front of me were in a conversation and when I caught up with them, they received me warmly and with a smile.  I asked "Are you training for a race"? One of them replied, "No, just training for life and chatting away." I told them that I was a priest and that running is a form of training for life, to embrace whatever challenges God places in front of you, like this gradual uphill and humidity that we are feeling right now.  We laughed and then I finished my 12 mile run.  Another good day on the trail...thank you, Jesus!

 Tomorrow evening, I will begin my annual 8 day silent retreat at Our Lady of Bethesda, followed by 2 weeks of vacation with my brother priests.  My service will resume when I return to DC on August 14th.  I am looking forward to this special time of prayer with my best friend, Jesus Christ, and some time to physically recharge the batteries with my brother priests on vacation.  Have a blessed summer ahead!

This year’s annual 8 day silent retreat took on a different twist, as I will celebrate my 25th anniversary to the priesthood on December 24, 2023.  I had plenty of time to reflect with Christ on the mystery of this incredible gift…all of the Masses, Confessions, mission trips, World Youth Days, special "Holy Spirit moments”, marathon ministry, etc.. I am so grateful to Christ for the incredible gift and mystery of this priestly calling, and I look forward to my next 25 years, focused mainly on deepening my friendship with HIM…trying my best not to get in His way or slow Him down!
 I am heading out to vacation tomorrow with my brother priests…back again on August 14th. 

God bless you,
Fr. Michael Sliney, LC

My first 10 miler since my marathon last Sunday.  I reflected on why I cramped up during my race and I am pretty sure it was due to overall dehydration.  I averaged close to 60 miles of training per week and unfortunately I simply forgot to drink more water and electrolytes during this process...besides at meals and during the run.  I felt lethargic and tired during the entire process and race day was not much different.  Since starting my day with hydration (before coffee) and bringing my "filled" water bottle off the shelf and onto my desk, I am feeling so much better with more energy and more bounce on my runs and during the day for my priestly ministry.  Grateful to have figured this out before my next training cycle!

Marathon ministry!  As I approached the 3 mile mark on the Capital Crescent Trail, I caught up to four runners around my age going at an 810 pace.  One was an ultra marathoner and the others had run Chicago and other races.  When I told them I was a Catholic priest and they saw my Boston shirt, one of the guys said, “It’s funny, we were just talking about how you can trust to hire or work with someone professionally if you know they go to Church on Sundays and have Faith as their compass....then we run into a priest who has run the Boston Marathon!” I responded by saying, “You really need to be ALL IN, whether it is your marriage or your Faith, or it will be really difficult to persevere.  This marathon training can help with creating a mindset to push yourself hard on the trails, so God can then challenge you to grow in the day to day.” 
  A few miles later, a younger 40 year old runner blew by me at a 740 pace,...the Holy Spirit told me to catch up to him.  He qualified for Boston 25’, so we talked Boston for the first few minutes.  Then I shifted to Faith.  He told me that he was married in a Catholic Church in Reston, Va. but he and his wife had not been practicing for awhile.  I mentioned a few Catholic Churches near where he lives in Alexandria, Va., so he seemed open to checking these out. We gave each other the fist pump and he left with a smile. 
  On mile 10, I saw a runner dressed up in a full Santa Claus outfit running towards me.  I shouted, “I love the outfit!  God bless you!  He smiled and responded, “Likewise!” and then shook his fist in the air saying, “Amen!!”
Allow the Holy Spirit to chisel!
